people have made an annual ritual of appealing to the school board 
to rescind the ban then quietly accepting a refusal that came as 
regularly as a final exam foxs class was different 
fox is among 21 purdy students and their parents who filed suit 
in 1986 asking the courts to strike down the ban as an 
unconstitutional encroachment of religious values on public life 
fox said fellow students have told him theyre against dancing 
because parents and ministers have told them it is a sin 
prodancers believe the ban unique among southern missouri 
school districts has endured because many in the community have a 
southern baptistinspired opposition to dancing 
thats not true said ransom ellis iii the attorney 
representing the school board the motivation was purely 
secular 
ellis said he would not expand on his argument because it would 
mean revealing evidence he planned to present in court 
us district judge russell clark has set aside four days 
beginning monday to hear the case in springfield clark was also 
considering a countersuit filed by the school district in which 
officials seek 1 million in damages claiming students and parents 
have harassed them over the dancing issue 
the suit filed by students and parents with backing from the 
american civil liberties union seeks a court order to keep the 
school from enforcing the dance ban attorneys fees and 1 in 
damages 
in 1986 purdy students signed a petition in support of a school 
dance and asked for their parents help when they took the request 
before the school board they were met with resistance organized in 
local churches so many people were drawn to the school board 
meeting at which the ban was challenged that it had to be moved to 
the high school gymnasium 
dance supporters were unable to get the school board to end the 
ban though they followed the petition drive with a rally that drew 
national attention the students invited stars of the musical 
footloose a movie about a fictional texas town where dancing 
was banned to the rally actors kevin bacon and lori singer were 
unable to attend 
in april 1986 school district voters reelected by wide margins 
the antidancing board members 
the controversy escalated to the point where dance supporters 
and opponents walked on opposite sides of the street 
a lot of people refer to me as a troublemaker an outsider 
said joan fox george foxs mother 
her family has lived in purdy for 13 years but remain newcomers 
in the eyes of lifelong residents mrs fox said it hasnt helped 
that she is a vocal supporter of what she says is her childrens 
right to dance at school 
they shouldnt be barred from homecoming and prom at school 
its a public school she said 
