<TEXT>
michael dukakis and jesse jackson agreed 
saturday to an overhaul of democratic party rules and avoided the 
possibility of a contentious floor fight at next months national 
convention 
under the agreement the number of super delegates to the 
1992 convention will be cut nearly in half and all other delegates 
would be awarded to presidential candidates in proportion to public 
support 
jackson meeting saturday with local campaign officials in san 
juan puerto rico said the agreement represented a victory for 
the people a victory for democracy 
jackson had complained that party rules did not allow him to get 
the delegates he said were warranted by his popular support he had 
said that he would carry his fight to the convention floor to get 
the rules changed 
i think that weve made a lot of steps forward in a lot of 
areas that rev jackson has been concerned about said harold 
ickes who negotiated for jackson on the rules changes 
of the 643 super delegates to the convention jackson who won 
29 percent of the vote in the primaries had just 55 dukakis who 
won 57 percent of the vote had 362 according to the associated 
press delegate count 
the super delegates party leaders and politicians who 
automatically hold seats as convention delegates are not bound to 
support a presidential candidate based on results of the primaries 
or caucuses 
and while the democratic party has no winnertakeall 
states it does have a few states in which direct election of 
delegates or winnertakemore systems are used 
dukakis used both of those aspects of the partys rules to give 
him the margin of delegates he needed to clinch the democratic 
presidential nomination he also intensively sought support from 
super delegates often making telephone calls to them himself 
currently dukakis has 2384 delegates overall while jackson has 
1132 
the dukakis campaign supported the rules changes but tad 
devine director of delegate selection for dukakis said it was not 
being done to buy peace with jackson 
hardly devine said i think it represents a compromise on 
the part of both campaigns it reflects a spirit of cooperation and 
good will 
the harmony between the two campaigns meant that the partys 
rules committee meeting this weekend was being cut from two days to 
one and probably would issue no dissenting reports when its 
business was finished devine said 
both campaigns said the negotiations had been going on for 
several days and stretched into the early hours of saturday 
morning however occasional snags were still being worked out on 
some issued during the rules committee meeting as a dozen or so 
representatives of the campaigns talked in a tight huddle at the 
back of the room 
the 186member committee approved the rules changes on saturday 
without dissent but the proposals still need to be ratified by the 
full convention next month in order to take effect for the 1992 
presidential campaign 
though adoption of this proposal doesnt put us in the 
promised land it puts us further down the road said warren 
bracy a committee member and jackson supporter from ann arbor 
mich of reducing the strength of super delegates 
rep wendell ford dky kept the metaphor this may not be 
the promised land but it does represent some milk and honey 
devine said dukakis did use the current system to his advantage 
but still would have won the nomination even if the proposed rules 
changes were in place 
i dont deny that we took a look at the delegate selection 
process in 1988 and developed strategies based on the way the 
process is structured devine said 
under the proposed changes the number of super delegates would 
be reduced to 394 by denying automatic delegate status to most 
members of the democratic national committee automatic delegate 
status would be reserved for democratic governors most members of 
congress and top two party leaders in each state and the partys 
national officers 
the system would return to rules used in 1984 when dnc members 
had priority for seats at the convention but had to compete for 
them and had to declare a presidential preference 
super delegates currently represent about 15 percent of the 
delegates to the convention under the proposed rules that would 
be cut to about 10 percent 
in addition states such as illinois and new jersey which 
picked their national convention delegates directly from the 
primary ballot would be compelled to adopt systems to award the 
delegates proportionally another handful of states including 
ohio new york and florida award extra delegates to the candidate 
receiving the most votes in their primaries and those systems 
too would have to be changed in four years 
the agreement also called for nudging states toward picking new 
dnc members based on whom they support for president and in 
proportion to results of the primary or caucus in that state 
states adopting this rule would be allowed to name one extra member 
apiece to the dnc 
in other business saturday the committee voted to recognize the 
district of columbia as a state giving mayor marion barry an 
automatic seat at the 1988 convention as a governor 
the committee without debate named house speaker jim wright as 
permanent chairman of this years national convention no mention 
was made of a house ethics committee investigation of some of 
wrights financial dealings 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

