<DOCNO> AP880625-0179 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
precautions taken by health care workers to 
protect themselves from the aids virus have led to a shortage of 
the latex and vinyl gloves used in the medical profession 
it is difficult to pinpoint the degree of the shortage because 
manufacturers are reluctant to release production figures and such 
numbers are not available from industry groups or the government 
but there is general agreement that availability has sharply 
declined in the past year since federal health officials urged 
health care professionals to take increased care to protect 
themselves from disease organisms that can be transmitted through 
body fluids 
there does seem to be a shortage of gloves in the united 
states said dr j thomas lowe spokesman for the us food and 
drug administration in washington which regulates the medical 
glove industry the glove industry is continuing to gear up the 
production and marketing of gloves to meet the increased demand 
the sharp and relatively sudden increase in glove use put a 
pinch on manufacturers capacity said les jacobson a spokesman 
for baxter international in deerfield ill a major producer of 
medical gloves 
the immediate cause was probably the encouragement of the cdc 
centers for disease control and the american dental association 
urging doctors and dentists to glove up whenever they come in 
contact with a patients body fluids jacobson said for many 
health care workers that was all the motivation they needed to 
glove up 
our demand has doubled in the last two years 
jeff leebaw spokesman for johnson amp johnson in new brunswick 
nj said his companys glove manufacturing plant in arlington 
texas has been operating 24 hours a day for more than a year and 
is planning to add more production equipment 
also he said the company has canceled glove orders from 
nonmedical customers 
the demand has increased quite a bit in connection with the 
aids problem and the concern in general with disease 
transmission leebaw said 
jacobson said the shortage is mainly a matter of production 
capacity rather than a shortage of the materials needed to make 
the gloves latex the glove of choice for surgeons is made from 
rubber while vinyl gloves are totally synthetic 
baxter last year constructed a new glove plant in malaysia and 
is planning another facility there jacobson said the company also 
has four us plants and three in europe 
judy smith a spokeswoman for emory university hospital in 
atlanta said the hospital has felt the shortage though it has not 
reached the point where medical service would be threatened 
instead she said it has more often been a problem of 
convenience with emory personnel sometimes not able to get the 
type or size of glove they want 
but we have not had any problems that would have resulted in a 
slowdown or shutdown in service she said 
because emory is an established hospital its list of vendors is 
long and thus the facility has several sources of gloves ms smith 
said but its purchasers have had to work hard to make sure the 
hospital is adequately stocked 
the cdc said gloves should be used whenever an individual might 
come in contact with a patients blood which poses the greatest 
threat for transmission of the virus that causes aids and the 
hepatitis b virus gloves also were advised for protection from 
numerous other body fluids 
jacobson said he expects demand for gloves to remain high 
though it probably will level off at some point 
i dont think well get the sudden sharp increase again 
jacobson said everyone who needs to know about gloving up knows 
now 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

