planes with significant corrosion problems and needed a new 
maintenance program according to a published report 
the washington post reported in its sunday editions that the 
seattlebased boeing co urged aloha to replace corroded fuselage 
panels on its four most heavily flown jets including the boeing 
737 involved in the april 28 accident 
boeing also urged the airline to take the planes out of service 
in the spring for permanent repairs inspections and to complete 
all deferred maintenance the post said citing documents that it 
said are part of the government investigation into the incident in 
which a section of the planes roof ripped off during flight 
in a nov 13 letter boeing advised the airline aloha has a 
highfrequency flight schedule and operates in a highly corrosive 
environment these factors certainly contribute to the corrosion 
and fatigue damage observed on the two airplanes surveyed 
this as well as the practice of repainting the airplane before 
and during inspections deferring repairs andor making temporary 
instead of terminating permanent repairs contributes to our 
mutual concerns wrote boeing 
the manufacturer also urged aloha to develop a new maintenance 
program that would assure thorough and frequent inspections as well 
as preventive maintenance on alohas aging planes the post said 
the recommendations were made after a team of boeing engineers 
visited aloha last fall to collect data for its aging fleet 
research program the newspaper said quoting from a 150page 
document 
the document consists of boeings november maintenance 
evaluation and dozens of recommendations as well as listings of 
the highlights of september october and january inspections of 
three older aloha jets the report also includes material 
describing boeings findings in the aging fleet survey program 
