<TEXT>
after viewing the drought as a reason to shun 
stocks some strategists see it as a chance to buy into companies 
that could profit by selling products ranging from hybrid seeds to 
welldrilling rigs 
food processors fertilizer makers seed distributors farm 
equipment manufacturers and irrigation companies are getting 
increased scrutiny as possible investment opportunities because of 
the drought which has withered much of this years crops and sent 
corn wheat and soybean prices soaring 
the thinking is that farmers will have to invest heavily for the 
1989 harvest and that food companies will enjoy better profits from 
higher prices 
for example pioneer hibred international one of the largest 
hybrid seedcorn producers has attracted some attention as a 
possible beneficiary partly because of its advanced research into 
droughtresistant strains 
these people have been through this before and are 
exceedingly familiar with drought conditions said laurence c 
day a stock strategist at the clayton mo office of the 
investment firm newhard cook amp co they are by far the superior 
company in this business 
freighthauling companies especially railroads and truckers 
also appear wellpositioned to exploit the barge backups on the 
mississippi river which have drastically reduced the amount of 
grain shipped to food processors 
certainly the transportation aspect of the agriculture market 
is going to be a winner here because most farmers are going to be 
very quick to get their product to market said jack barbanel a 
futures expert at gruntal amp co in new york if somebody has a 
better system for transporting grains its certainly a moneymaking 
situation 
a projected shortage of soybeans also has some wall street 
analysts puzzling out the profitable opportunities soybeans are 
getting heavy attention because they are used in a wide range of 
products unrelated to food from unleaded gasoline to cosmetics 
a few strategists are even recommending poultry companies their 
argument goes like this cattle farmers will be forced to slaughter 
their herds this year because they cant afford to feed them this 
will create a shortterm beef and pork glut but by next year acute 
shortages are certain with meat prices soaring then more 
consumers may switch to cheaper chicken 
others are focusing on large fastfood chains that will likely 
benefit from higher food prices mcdonalds for example has been 
touted by some brokers recently because it is expected to get 
increased royalties linked to higher sales revenue from its 
franchised restaurants 
wall street initially seized on the drought as a sell signal 
because it implies sharply higher inflation which theoretically 
raises pressure on the federal reserve to hike interest rates and 
thus erodes the comparative value of stocks 
but as other evidence has emerged that inflation remains tame 
the drought theme has been transformed into an obscure form of good 
news in the stock market some investment strategists see it as the 
vehicle for companies to lock in greater profit margins by raising 
prices now 
in classic supplydemand fashion commodity prices could fall 
next year said john bierbusse an analyst who follows cereal 
companies for the investment firm of ag edwards amp sons in st 
louis mo but you and i both know that cereal prices dont go 
down 
others however havent flocked to the drought theme they say 
the drought could hurt food companies especially those lacking 
longterm commitments to buy grain at predrought prices they also 
say the disaster could ruin fragile rural economies and will 
clearly spill into other areas 
theres going to be some impact said william tiritilli 
vice president and director of research at rodman amp renshaw inc in 
chicago retailers and banks could get hurt a farmer who doesnt 
have crops cant pay loans back 
whatever the ultimate outcome of the drought on wall streets 
collective thinking some believe it will be shortlived soon to 
be displaced by another significant economic event 
the attention span on wall street is about 30 minutes said 
robert sobel a market historian and author if it rains 
tomorrow theyll forget about it completely 
</TEXT>
